Belady's Anomaly: In Test Case 2, why does adding a 4th frame cause MORE page faults than having only 3 frames? This seems counterintuitive.
      FIFO rigidly evicts the oldest page, regardless of how soon that page will be needed again. In specific access patterns like Test Case
      2, having 3 frames cycles the pages out at a rhythm that accidentally keeps upcoming pages in memory. When you increase the capacity to 
      4 frames, the internal timeline changes. The system keeps older pages around slightly longer, which pushes the eviction of a currently 
      needed page into the exact moment the program needs to access it again, resulting in more page faults.
Data Structures: Why do we need both a Queue AND a Set? What would happen if we only used a Queue?
      We use the Queue to maintain the chronological order of pages (First-In, First-Out), so we know exactly which page is the oldest and needs
      to be evicted. We use the Set to provide constant-time $O(1)$ lookups to quickly check if a page is currently in memory.
      If we only used a Queue, every time a page is requested, we would have to iterate through the entire queue to check if the page exists. 
      This would change the lookup time to $O(N)$ where N is the number of frames, slowing down the algorithm significantly for large memory sizes.
Performance: If memory access takes 200 nanoseconds and a page fault takes 8 milliseconds, calculate the effective access time for Test Case 1 with 3 frames. (Use the formula from the lesson)
      Memory access time = 200 ns
      Page fault time = 8 milliseconds = 8,000,000 ns
      Test Case 1 (3 frames) Fault Rate ($p$) = 75.0% = 0.75
      Test Case 1 (3 frames) Hit Rate = 25.0% = 0.25
      Formula: Effective Access Time (EAT) = (Hit Rate * Memory Access Time) + (Fault Rate * Page Fault Time)
      EAT = (0.25 * 200 ns) + (0.75 * 8,000,000 ns)
      EAT = 50 ns + 6,000,000 ns
      Effective Access Time = 6,000,050 ns (or ~6 ms)
Pattern Analysis: Which test case had the worst performance with 3 frames? Why did that particular access pattern cause so many page faults?
      Test Case 3 (Looping Pattern: [1, 2, 3, 4, 1, 2...]) had the worst performance with a 100% fault rate. This happens because the program 
      cycles through 4 distinct pages continuously, but only has 3 frames available. By the time the program loops back to request page 1, 
      page 1 has just been evicted to make room for page 4. This constant cycle of evicting the exact page that will be needed next is a 
      worst-case scenario known as "thrashing."
Real World: Based on your observations, why do you think modern operating systems don't use pure FIFO for page replacement?
      Modern operating systems avoid pure FIFO because it completely ignores the principle of locality—how recently or frequently a page is 
      being used. FIFO might aggressively kick out a heavily used variable or core library simply because it was loaded into memory first. 
      Coupled with the fact that adding physical memory can inexplicably degrade performance (Belady's Anomaly), pure FIFO is too inefficient. 
      Modern systems use more intelligent algorithms like Least Recently Used (LRU) or Clock (Second-Chance) algorithms, which make eviction 
      decisions based on actual page usage.
